COMPUTE WINT,0.5717213114754098,"C.1
Why we use secure comparison as complexity metric"
COMPUTE WINT,0.5737704918032787,"MPC is efÔ¨Åcient on linear operations when using arithmetic shares. The sum of two arithmetic
shares ‚ü®a‚ü©+ ‚ü®b‚ü©result in share ‚ü®a + b‚ü©. However, this is not the case for non-linear operations such
as ‚ü®a‚ü©> ‚ü®b‚ü©, since the operation performed and the type of secret sharing are not of the same nature."
COMPUTE WINT,0.5758196721311475,"These type of non-linear operations such as multiplication, comparisons, and equality require in-
creased computations, such as generation of correlated randomness between parties. There have
been many works on improving the efÔ¨Åciency of secure comparisons. (DamgÀöard et al., 2006) pro-
vide a secure comparison protocol which uses O(‚Ñìlog ‚Ñì) secure multiplications, where ‚Ñì= log p
and p is the prime used for the Ô¨Åeld the secret shares are computed over. (Nishide & Ohta, 2007)
improved the complexity of secure comparison to O(‚Ñì) secure multiplications."
COMPUTE WINT,0.5778688524590164,"Thus a large portion of the evaluation of a function in MPC is due to the computation of non-linear
operations. Computing median intuitively involves expensive comparison operations, and therefore
we choose the number of secure comparisons needed as a metric for computational complexity of
the protocols."
